snippet.textDisplay: 2x the bat speed but only marginally more distance? The HowStuffWorks page on wood vs. aluminum bats  estimates that for every extra MPH of bat speed, a baseball will fly another 8 feet. An extra 125 MPH on your swing then, that should mean a homer an insane 1,000 feet longer than the record. I guess the perfect bat impact might be a 1 in 1,000 kind of occurrence, though. Or 1 in 10,000. Not to mention a big guy swinging a bat might simply deliver energy into the ball in a way more effective way than that box. The mechanics of a batter's swing, the human body's flexibility...who knows what's involved. Also, unless I read it wrong, an article on Diamond Kinetics on exit velocity seems to state that +1 MPH pitch speed will give you an extra foot of distance. Then there's pitch spin. THEN THERE'S WEATHER.
